As we build our notebook, we'll follow this structure:

Use # %% for code cells
Use # %% [markdown] with triple quotes for documentation
Keep a logical flow from data loading to exploration to visualization
Document our process and findings along the way


These are the constraints and standards the agent must follow to maintain quality.

- Memory Visualization Standard: Do not use simple line charts for memory usage. Always use Stacked Area Plots that distinguish between Used, Free, and Cached memory. This is required to accurately represent Linux memory management, where high cache usage is healthy and distinct from active application memory.

- CPU Granularity Rule: Visualizations for CPU activity must support Per-Core Granularity (e.g., separate lines for cpu0, cpu1). Do not rely solely on a total system average, as this hides single-threaded process bottlenecks.

- Time-Series Synchronization: All temporal graphs must utilize a common X-Axis (Time). Timestamps must be synchronized across different metric plots to allow for manual visual correlation (e.g., aligning a CPU spike with a log entry).